# Advanced Science O/X
> Deeper physics, chemistry, and biology
@languageCode: en
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.science.advanced/

According to Einstein's equation E=mc², mass and energy are equivalent and can be converted into each other. | O | E=mc² expresses the equivalence of mass and energy, a cornerstone of modern physics.
The speed of light in a vacuum is approximately 300,000 kilometers per second. | O | Light travels at about 299,792 km/s in a vacuum.
An atom's chemical identity is determined by its number of neutrons. | X | An element is defined by its number of protons (atomic number), not neutrons.
DNA base pairing follows the rule that adenine pairs with thymine and guanine pairs with cytosine. | O | In DNA, A pairs with T and G pairs with C via complementary base pairing.
Absolute zero (0 kelvin) is the lowest possible temperature on the thermodynamic scale. | O | Absolute zero is the theoretical lower limit of temperature, about -273.15°C.
Enzymes are biological catalysts that lower the activation energy of chemical reactions. | O | Enzymes speed up reactions by lowering activation energy and are not consumed in the process.
Sound can travel through the vacuum of outer space just like light. | X | Sound needs a medium (like air) to travel and cannot propagate through a vacuum; light can.
The mitochondria are often described as the powerhouse of the cell because they produce ATP. | O | Mitochondria generate ATP through cellular respiration, powering the cell.
Which subatomic particle carries a negative electric charge? | 1)Electron 2)Proton 3)Neutron 4)Photon | 1 | Electrons carry a negative charge; protons are positive and neutrons are neutral.
How many chromosomes are in a normal human body (somatic) cell? | 1)46 2)23 3)48 4)44 | 1 | Human somatic cells have 23 pairs, for a total of 46 chromosomes.
Q: What gas do plants absorb from the air and use during photosynthesis? (name the gas) | A: carbon dioxide;co2;co₂ | Plants absorb carbon dioxide and, using sunlight, produce glucose and release oxygen.
Q: What is the chemical symbol for water? (formula) | A: h2o;h₂o | Water is made of two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom, written H2O.
Newton's third law states that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction. | O | When one body exerts a force on another, the second exerts an equal force in the opposite direction.
The pH scale ranges from 0 to 7, with 7 being the most acidic value. | X | The pH scale runs from 0 to 14; 7 is neutral, and lower numbers (toward 0) are more acidic.
Which particle is the carrier (mediator) of the electromagnetic force? | 1)Photon 2)Gluon 3)Neutrino 4)Electron | 1 | The photon is the exchange particle that mediates the electromagnetic force.
Photosynthesis converts light energy into chemical energy stored in glucose. | O | Plants use sunlight to build glucose, storing energy in its chemical bonds.
Q: What force pulls objects toward the center of the Earth? (name the force) | A: gravity;gravitation;gravitational force | Gravity is the attractive force that pulls masses toward one another, including toward Earth's center.
Isotopes of the same element differ in their number of protons. | X | Isotopes have the same number of protons but different numbers of neutrons.
The second law of thermodynamics says the entropy of an isolated system tends to increase over time. | O | In an isolated system, disorder (entropy) tends to rise, setting a direction for spontaneous processes.
What is the most abundant gas in Earth's atmosphere? | 1)Oxygen 2)Carbon dioxide 3)Nitrogen 4)Hydrogen | 3 | Nitrogen makes up about 78 percent of Earth's atmosphere, far more than oxygen.
A catalyst is permanently consumed and used up during a chemical reaction. | X | A catalyst speeds up a reaction without being consumed, so it can be reused.
Ohm's law states that voltage equals current multiplied by resistance. | O | Ohm's law is written V = I × R, relating voltage, current, and resistance in a circuit.
Q: What is the process by which a liquid changes into a gas called? (single word) | A: evaporation;vaporization;vaporisation | Vaporization, commonly called evaporation at a surface, is the change of a liquid into a gas.
Ribosomes are the organelles chiefly responsible for producing the cell's ATP. | X | Ribosomes build proteins; ATP is mainly produced by the mitochondria.
Noble gases are largely chemically inert because they have full outer electron shells. | O | With complete valence shells, noble gases have little tendency to gain, lose, or share electrons.
Which type of electromagnetic radiation carries the highest energy? | 1)Radio waves 2)Gamma rays 3)Visible light 4)Microwaves | 2 | Gamma rays have the shortest wavelength and highest frequency, so they carry the most energy.
Red light has a shorter wavelength than blue light. | X | Red light has a longer wavelength than blue light; blue is at the shorter-wavelength end of visible light.
Water expands when it freezes, so ice is less dense than liquid water. | O | Ice's crystal structure spreads molecules farther apart, making it less dense so it floats.
Q: What is the chemical symbol for the element gold? | A: au | Gold's symbol is Au, from its Latin name aurum.
In a covalent bond, electrons are transferred completely from one atom to another. | X | Covalent bonds involve shared electrons; complete electron transfer describes ionic bonds.
The Doppler effect describes a change in a wave's observed frequency due to relative motion between source and observer. | O | As a source and observer move relative to each other, the observed frequency shifts, as with a passing siren.
What is the SI base unit of electric current? | 1)Volt 2)Watt 3)Ohm 4)Ampere | 4 | The ampere (A) is the SI base unit of electric current.
Mitosis produces four genetically unique daughter cells from one parent cell. | X | Mitosis yields two genetically identical daughter cells; four genetically varied cells come from meiosis.
Kinetic energy is the energy an object possesses because of its motion. | O | A moving object carries kinetic energy that increases with its mass and the square of its speed.
Q: What term describes an animal that eats only plants? | A: herbivore;herbivorous | A herbivore is an animal whose diet consists mainly or entirely of plants.
The half-life of a radioactive isotope is the time it takes for all of its atoms to decay. | X | A half-life is the time for half of the atoms in a sample to decay, not all of them.
